The natural frequency of an undamped spring-mass system is given by the formula $\omega_n = \sqrt{k/m}$, where $k$ is the spring stiffness and $m$ is the mass. Plugging in the given values of $k = 20$ kN/m and $m = 3$ kg, we get:
\begin{align*}
\omega_n &= \sqrt{\frac{20 \times 10^3 \text{ N/m}}{3 \text{ kg}}}\n&= \sqrt{\frac{20,000 \text{ N/m}}{3 \text{ kg}}}\n&= \sqrt{6666.67 \text{ rad/s}}\n&= 101.64 \text{ rad/s}
\end{align*}
Converting to frequency in Hz:
$f_n = \frac{\omega_n}{2\pi} = \frac{101.64 \text{ rad/s}}{2\pi} = 16.18 \text{ Hz}$
Rounding to the nearest integer, the natural frequency of the system is 16 Hz.
